# Git Commands

> This document defines mandatory project conventions.
> These rules apply to both human contributors and AI-generated code.

## Always on

### Commit Message Format

Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) format:

```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

### Types

- `feat`: New feature
- `fix`: Bug fix
- `docs`: Documentation changes
- `style`: Code style changes (formatting, missing semicolons, etc.)
- `refactor`: Code refactoring
- `perf`: Performance improvements
- `test`: Adding or updating tests
- `chore`: Maintenance tasks (dependencies, build, etc.)
- `build`: Build system changes
- `ci`: CI/CD changes

### Examples

```
feat: add dead letter queue API endpoints

fix: handle database reconnection errors

docs: update README with installation instructions

test: add unit tests for OutboxRepository
```

### Git Commands

- Use `git add .` to stage all changes
- Use `git commit -m "type: description"` for commits
- Use `git log --oneline` to view commit history
